reviewText: Jimmy and Brian are a good combination always. I guess it's still fascinating to watch Brian in an informal role. He's Ed McMahon to Johnny Carson here. Entertaining, but a bit of a slow start.
Very interesting, funny and got to know Jimmy Fallon better.  Wish it had clips of shows. I would recommend this to friends.
This was fun to watch, Jimmy Fallon and Brian Williams obviously have a great friendship. Who knew Brian Williams was comedic?
These are two of my favorite people, so I thought this was great!  Lot of laughs, but some good insight, too.

I thought this was an extremely entertaining andan educational.

you not only learn about Jimmy Kimmel but you learn so much about NBC studios

very interesting highly recommended make sure you watch all the way through

Great to get an understanding of the early plans Jimmy had for the show and comparing them to how the show has evolved. Jimmy has a real sense of fun and imparts it into the show. If I didn't know better I would say he was Canadian!

Jimmy Fallon is amazing - he is the perfect entertainer and is self-deprecating to the right amount with a touch of silliness and awareness that is clearly instinctual with him.  I truly consider him to be a comedic genius - of course one who surrounds himself with amazing writers and an innate passion for what he does.  I can't say enough about him.
Must see for any Fallon fan!
Very funny content.
Enjoy all the Paley Center interviews and who doesn't love Jimmy Fallon?

I love Jimmy Fallon.

Fallon and Williams. Always a top notch funny duo. This was, of course, before the Tonight Show gig and gives some insight into Fallon's dreams and early background. He's goofy from the start. I've watched this maybe six times and laughed every time. (And I think Williams should take over The Daily Show...)
Laugh out loud! What a great combo.
Love Jimmy Fallon and Brian Williamss; they are comical together.

Amazing. Jimmy Fallon is incredible and has a personality that makes you want to just sit down and have a cup of coffee and hang out with him. This is the atmosphere he has created in the Tonight Show. His humble and warm personality along with his wit and incredible sense of humor overflow in this interview. Brian Williams plays straight man like no other to Fallon.
Every time I have seen Fallon open up and show more of who he is I am more and more intrigued by him. Well done Paley Center! I would love to see another current interview of Jimmy since the takeover of the Tonight Show!

Jimmy has such a likable persona & a fun chemistry with Brian. The whole interview was excellent, he even took that troll of a question at the end in stride. If you liked this, check out his episode on Jerry Seinfeld's Comedians in Cars Getting Coffee, you'll enjoy it.
Lost interest. Sort of OK but not compelling.
Good interview. He is down to earth and relatable.

Though the interview is slightly more than an hour long, there is so much dialogue packed into it that I felt like I saw a longer interview. This is a good take on Jimmy Fallon - how genuine he is and pardon the pun, how rooted he is.  Roots from family and roots from Roots.  What more could anyone need.  But the bottom line is, give that man just a pencil and piece of paper and no doubt, he will not only use it to write scripts, but make paper airplanes, other origamy, maybe a hat or a puppet, a mask, and so on.  Jimmy's talents were in his genes.  His family brought out his best by letting him do what he wanted to do.  The interview makes you understand that through all the very funny talk he shares about his life as a standup comic - mortal, on his mononuclear monkeypad, monopolizing the monologue while monitoring his fellow monosomies.  What more could an entertainer in funny business enrobe themselves with?  (ha!)
Outstanding.  Fallon's energy is contagious.  Funniest man in America. Second in the world only to the Queen of England.

No. A nervy, fidgety smirk accompanied by an over-enjoyment of your own jokes is not technically "funny." About the only upside I can see with his career is that he his energetic. However, rather than putting said energy into maybe subtlety (or a different approach), he overdoes damn near every joke or worse yet, laughs at his own stuff?

Getting movie and show deals means you have a terrific agent, or you saved some hollywood insider's life. But this guy SUCKS at comedy.
